England":"England"},"en":{"1285–1327":"1285–1327","1270–1295":"1270–1295","1286–1327":"1286–1327","1287–Female":"1287–Deceased","–1398":"–1398","1286–Female":"1286–Deceased","1310–1381":"1310–1381","1325–1380":"1325–1380","1327–1364":"1327–1364","1245–1288":"1245–1288","1248–1291":"1248–1291","1286":"1286","1285":"1285","1295":"1295","1381":"1381","1380":"1380","1270":"1270","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1248":"1248","1269":"1269","1245":"1245","1288":"1288","1310":"1310","1398":"1398","1364":"1364","1287":"1287","1317":"1317","Market Bosworth, Leicestershire, England":"Market Bosworth, Leicestershire, England","Market Bosworth, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Market Bosworth, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Shute, Devon, England":"Shute, Devon, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Payne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Pai(e)n</i>, <i>Pagen</i> (from Latin <i>Paganus</i>), a fairly common personal name among Normans. It derived from a word that originally meant ‘villager, rustic’, later ‘heathen’, but it had doubtless lost these connotations in its use as a late medieval personal name. This name has also been established in Ireland since the 14th century.","History: Thomas Payne, who was a freeman of Plymouth Colony in 1639, was the founder of a large American family, which included Robert Treat Paine (1731–1814), one of the signers of the Declaration of Independence. See also   Paine  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Payn","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Payne  ."]},{"name":"Payen","meanings":["French: from the Old French personal name <i>Pagen</i>, <i>Paien</i>, from Latin <i>Paganus</i>, from <i>paganus</i> ‘country-dweller’, a derivative of <i>pagus</i> ‘of or relating to the countryside’, possibly given to a child not yet baptized (because of its later sense of ‘pagan, heathen’). Alternatively, a nickname for a country-born person. This surname is also found in the West Indies (mainly Haiti) and Mauritius.","English: variant of   Payne  ."]},{"name":"Pagan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luis, Juan, Angel, Carlos, Rafael, Ramon, Pedro, Francisco, Jesus, Miguel, Julio.","Spanish and Catalan: Castilianized form (<b>Pagán</b>) of Catalan <b>Pagà</b>, from the Late Latin personal name <i>Paganus</i>, which as a derivative of Latin <i>pagus</i> ‘outlying village’ originally meant ‘villager’ (see   Payne  ). Alternatively, in some cases, a topographic name from Catalan <i>pagà</i> ‘heath’ (from the same Latin word <i>pagus</i>).","English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Pai(e)n</i>, <i>Pagen</i>, from Late Latin <i>Paganus</i> (see   Payne  , compare 1 above)."]},{"name":"Paynes","meanings":["English: variant of   Payne  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Paine","meanings":["English: variant of   Payne  .","History: The author of the republican treatise <i>The Rights of Man</i>, Thomas Paine (1737–1809), left England for North America in the mid 1770s, where he became involved in the movement that led to independence. His pamphlet of 1776, <i>Common Sense</i>, influenced the Declaration of Independence and furnished some of the arguments justifying it."]},{"name":"Pank","meanings":["English (Norfolk): perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Pank(e)</i>. It could be a shortened form of <i>Pancok</i>, which is probably a pet form of <i>Pane</i> (see   Payne  ).","Sorbian: nickname from a diminutive of <i>pan</i> ‘mister, lord, landlord’ (see   Pan  ). Compare   Panke  ."]},{"name":"Pane","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Antonio, Salvatore, Aldo, Carmela, Carmine, Ciro, Concetta, Enzo, Giuseppe, Mario, Armando, Claudio, Macario, Remigio.","Italian: from <i>pane</i> ‘bread’, used as a metonymic occupational name for a baker or as a nickname meaning ‘good thing’, and also as a personal name. This surname is also found in southern France and Corsica.","English: variant of   Payne  ."]},{"name":"Panes","meanings":["English (Somerset): variant of   Payne  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Pannell","meanings":["English (southeastern):","possibly from Middle English <i>panel</i>, <i>panel(l)e</i> ‘cloth, saddle-cloth, saddle’ or ‘pane (of glass)’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a maker of such items.","from the Middle English personal name <i>Paynel</i> (Old French <i>Payenel</i>, Latin <i>Paganellus</i>), a pet form of   Payne   (from Latin <i>Paganus</i>)."]},{"name":"Penson","meanings":["English:","patronymic from the Middle English female personal name <i>Penn</i>, a pet form of <i>Pernel</i>, or perhaps from the Middle English personal name   Payne   + <i>-son</i>. See   Penn  ,   Parnell  .","habitational name from Penson in North Huish (Devon), which derives from the Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Payn(e)</i> (see   Payne  ) + Middle English <i>toun</i> ‘village, town, settlement’ (Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’)."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":5,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":30,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Payne V, Esquire was born in 1285, in Market Bosworth, Leicestershire, England, his father, Sir Thomas Robert Payne IV, Knights Templar, was 40 and his mother, Lady Mary Jane Avis - eol, was 37. He had at least 3 sons with Lady Catherine Sinclair. He died in 1327, in his hometown, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1285–1327":"1285–1327","1270–1295":"1270–1295","1286–1327":"1286–1327","1287–Female":"1287–Surnud","–1398":"–1398","1286–Female":"1286–Surnud","1310–1381":"1310–1381","1325–1380":"1325–1380","1327–1364":"1327–1364","1245–1288":"1245–1288","1248–1291":"1248–1291","1286":"1286","1285":"1285","1295":"1295","1381":"1381","1380":"1380","1270":"1270","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1248":"1248","1269":"1269","1245":"1245","1288":"1288","1310":"1310","1398":"1398","1364":"1364","1287":"1287","1317":"1317","Market Bosworth, Leicestershire, England":"Market Bosworth, Leicestershire, England","Market Bosworth, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Market Bosworth, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shute, Devon, England":"Shute, Devon, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1285–1327":"1285–1327","1270–1295":"1270–1295","1286–1327":"1286–1327","1287–Female":"1287–Kuollut","–1398":"–1398","1286–Female":"1286–Kuollut","1310–1381":"1310–1381","1325–1380":"1325–1380","1327–1364":"1327–1364","1245–1288":"1245–1288","1248–1291":"1248–1291","1286":"1286","1285":"1285","1295":"1295","1381":"1381","1380":"1380","1270":"1270","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1248":"1248","1269":"1269","1245":"1